        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Down</placeName>
                    <date>Tuesday Evening</date>
                    <salute>My dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>As Leonard will go to school tomorrow (Wednesday) afternoon will you be so kind as to let us have the note, properly addressed, about the sling.—<ref target="#foot.f2"/> His arm keeps quite comfortable.—</p>
<p>Your’s very faithfully | &amp; obliged | Ch. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="tnotes">
                <note xml:id="tnote.n1">(Wednesday)] <hi rend="italic">interl</hi> </note>
            </div>

            
            
            
            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The date is conjectured from a reference to ‘Lenny’s arm’ in <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1218.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Emma Darwin’s</ref> diary (DAR 242) for 22 April 1867. Stephen Engleheart was the village physician in Down and was frequently consulted by the Darwin family (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2662.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Freeman 1978</ref>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1230.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Leonard Darwin</ref> was a pupil at Clapham Grammar School in South London (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_4338.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">M. Keynes 1943</ref>).</note>
        </div>        
            
